So I wanted to share the perspective, in case it helps anybody else, too!

snippet.title: Is It Self-Sabotage Or Attachment Wounding?
snippet.description:
There's a common misconception about having an anxious attachment style, an avoidant attachment style or a fearful-avoidant attachment style, which is that the associated behaviors are maladaptive. But this is only true *in a particular context.*

What gets ignored too often in the attachment discourse is the strategic intelligence of our earliest impulses. Because our attachment styles are formed in a vacuum. And we do not heal them in one either.

This video focuses mostly on the controlling behaviors that are part and parcel with anxious-spectrum attachment issues (so, anxious and fearful-avoidant control responses) but the principles of noticing and setting boundaries around your own triggers can apply to pretty much anyone. 

It is impossible to heal from interpersonal trauma like attachment wounding without, at some point, becoming aware of how your wounding has impacted the people around you. This does not mean you are "toxic," "narcissistic" or otherwise fatally flawed. It means you're a human being trying to do better. And if you want to know where to begin, this video is for you.

snippet.title: Regular Avoidance Vs Attachment Avoidance
snippet.description:
ALRIGHT I was wondering when this series was going to start getting vulnerable and it turns out the answer is "Video 2." 

This video is a clarifier video. Based on a lot of convos I was having with people on here and on other social media platforms, I realized there was a linguistic nuance related to attachment styles that had a few people confused. And that word is the word 'avoidant.' It means something very specific in relation to attachment styles than it does in the regular sense of the term!

This video talks a lot about my personal experiences with falling in love as an avoidant spectrum (probably fearful avoidant) type. My experiences will not be everybody's experiences. It's also worth noting that I've spent years dissecting and finding language for my experiences so the way I describe them now was not the level of awareness I experienced them with at the time. There will be another video where I talk about that. 

But for now, here's the difference between normal avoidant behaviors and what we classify as attachment avoidance. Curious to hear how other avoidant spectrum individuals do or do not relate!
